{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_2788be2d5ffe53nFnIn5eNbziE","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d87743df7001RxoNqn5U3VXw6B","parts":[{"id":"prt_d87744848001fclc61Gh15d0Qo","messageID":"msg_d87743df7001RxoNqn5U3VXw6B","sessionID":"ses_2788be2d5ffe53nFnIn5eNbziE","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_040f1b80ed78431189ad2705","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/about/devenv.md"},"output":"<path>/workspace/docs/about/devenv.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: \n2: # Development environment\n3: \n4: This page describes a common development setup for working with Mopidy and\n5: Mopidy extensions. Of course, there may be other ways that work better for you\n6: and the tools you use, but here's one recommended way to do it.\n7: \n8: ## Initial setup\n9: \n10: The following steps help you get a good initial setup. They build on each other\n11: to some degree, so if you're not very familiar with Python development it might\n12: be wise to proceed in the order laid out here.\n13: \n14: ### Install Mopidy the regular way\n15: \n16: Install Mopidy the regular way. Mopidy has some non-Python dependencies which\n17: may be tricky to install. Thus we recommend to always start with a full regular\n18: Mopidy install, as described in installation. That is, if you're running\n19: e.g. Debian, start with installing Mopidy from Debian packages.\n20: \n21: ### Make a development workspace\n22: \n23: Make a directory to be used as a workspace for all your Mopidy development:\n24: \n25: ```console\n26: $ mkdir ~/mopidy-dev\n27: ```\n28: \n29: It will contain all the Git repositories you'll check out when working on\n30: Mopidy and extensions.\n31: \n32: ### Make a virtualenv\n33: \n34: Make a Python virtualenv for Mopidy development.\n35: The virtualenv will wall off Mopidy and its dependencies from the rest of your system.\n36: All development and installation of Python dependencies,\n37: versions of Mopidy, and extensions are done inside the virtualenv.\n38: This way your regular Mopidy install,\n39: which you set up in the first step,\n40: is unaffected by your hacking and will always be working.\n41: \n42: To create a virtualenv in the Mopidy workspace directory, run:\n43: \n44: ```console\n45: $ python3 -m venv ~/mopidy-dev/.venv\n46: ```\n47: \n48: Now, each time you open a terminal and want to activate the `mopidy`\n49: virtualenv, run:\n50: \n51: ```console\n52: $ . ~/mopidy-dev/.venv/bin/activate\n53: ```\n54: \n55: There are lots of ways to set up your shell to automatically activate the virtualenv,\n56: e.g. when changing directory into `~/mopidy-dev/` or a subdirectory.\n57: As this is just convenience and not strictly required,\n58: it is left as an exercise for the reader.\n59: \n60: ### Clone the repo from GitHub\n61: \n62: Once inside the virtualenv, it's time to clone the `mopidy/mopidy` Git repo\n63: from GitHub:\n64: \n65: ```console\n66: $ cd ~/mopidy-dev/\n67: $ git clone https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git\n68: ```\n69: \n70: When you've cloned the `mopidy` Git repo, `cd` into it:\n71: \n72: ```console\n73: $ cd ~/mopidy-dev/mopidy/\n74: ```\n75: \n76: With a fresh clone of the Git repo, you should start out on the `main`\n77: branch. This is where all features for the next feature release land. To\n78: confirm that you're on the right branch, run:\n79: \n80: ```console\n81: $ git branch\n82: ```\n83: \n84: ### Install Mopidy from the Git repo\n85: \n86: Next up, we'll want to run Mopidy from the Git repo. There's two reasons for\n87: this: first of all, it lets you easily change the source code, restart Mopidy,\n88: and see the change take effect. Second, it's a convenient way to keep at the\n89: bleeding edge, testing the latest developments in Mopidy itself or test some\n90: extension against the latest Mopidy changes.\n91: \n92: Assuming you're still inside the Git repo, use pip to install Mopidy from the\n93: Git repo in an \"editable\" form:\n94: \n95: ```console\n96: $ pip install --upgrade --editable .\n97: ```\n98: \n99: When using the `--editable` flag, the source code is not copied into the\n100: virtualenv's `site-packages` directory, but instead creates a link there\n101: pointing to the Git repo. This way, you can change the source code in the Git\n102: repo and the changes will be visible inside the virtualenv without having to\n103: reinstall Mopidy.\n104: \n105: It will also create a `mopidy` executable inside the virtualenv that will\n106: always run the latest code from the Git repo:\n107: \n108: ```console\n109: $ cat ~/mopidy-dev/.venv/bin/mopidy\n110: ...\n111: ```\n112: \n113: This file is on the path when the virtualenv is active, so you can run it from\n114: anywhere, simply by running:\n115: \n116: ```console\n117: $ mopidy\n118: ```\n119: \n120: /// tip\n121: It is also possible to run Python apps directly,\n122: e.g. using `python3 src/mopidy` directly on the\n123: `/mopidy-dev/mopidy/src/mopidy/` Python package directory.\n124: However, if you don't run the install command above,\n125: the extensions bundled with Mopidy will not be registered and made available\n126: for use, making Mopidy quite useless.\n127: ///\n128: \n129: Third, the install command will register the bundled Mopidy\n130: extensions so that Mopidy may find them through `importlib`.\n131: The result of this can be seen in a file named `entry_points.txt`\n132: which can be found inside the virtualenv dir, e.g.\n133: `/mopidy-dev/.venv/lib/python3.13/site-packages/Mopidy-4.0.0.dist-info/entry_points.txt`.\n134: The `entry_points.txt` file is of special interest as it shows both how\n135: the above executable and the bundled extensions are connected to the Mopidy\n136: source code:\n137: \n138: ```ini title=\"entry_points.txt\"\n139: [console_scripts]\n140: mopidy = mopidy._app.cli:app.meta\n141: \n142: [mopidy.ext]\n143: file = mopidy._exts.file:Extension\n144: http = mopidy._exts.http:Extension\n145: m3u = mopidy._exts.m3u:Extension\n146: softwaremixer = mopidy._exts.softwaremixer:Extension\n147: stream = mopidy._exts.stream:Extension\n148: ```\n149: \n150: ### Install development tools\n151: \n152: Before continuing, you will probably want to install the development tools we\n153: use as well. These can be installed into the active virtualenv by running:\n154: \n155: ```console\n156: $ cd ~/mopidy-dev/mopidy/\n157: $ pip install --upgrade --editable \".[dev]\"\n158: ```\n159: \n160: Note that this is the same command as you used to install Mopidy from the Git\n161: repo, with the addition of the `[dev]` suffix after `.`. This makes pip\n162: install the \"dev\" set of extra dependencies. Exactly what the \"dev\" set\n163: includes are defined in `pyproject.toml`. Since pip v25.1 you can\n164: instead do:\n165: \n166: ```console\n167: $ pip install --upgrade --group dev --editable .\n168: ```\n169: \n170: To upgrade the development tools in the future, just rerun the exact same\n171: command.\n172: \n173: ## Running Mopidy from Git\n174: \n175: As long as the virtualenv is activated, you can start Mopidy from any\n176: directory. Simply run:\n177: \n178: ```console\n179: $ mopidy\n180: ```\n181: \n182: To stop it again, press ++ctrl+c++.\n183: \n184: Every time you change code in Mopidy or an extension and want to see it\n185: live, you must restart Mopidy.\n186: \n187: If you want to iterate quickly while developing, it may sound a bit tedious to\n188: restart Mopidy for every minor change. Then it's useful to have tests to\n189: exercise your code...\n190: \n191: ## Running tests\n192: \n193: Mopidy has quite good test coverage, and we would like all new code going into\n194: Mopidy to come with tests.\n195: \n196: ### Test it all\n197: \n198: You need to know at least one command; the one that runs all the tests:\n199: \n200: ```console\n201: $ tox\n202: ```\n203: \n204: This will run exactly the same tests as our CI setup runs for all our\n205: branches and pull requests. If this command turns green, you can be quite\n206: confident that your pull request will get the green flag from CI as well,\n207: which is a requirement for it to be merged.\n208: \n209: As this is the ultimate test command, it's also the one taking the most time to\n210: run; up to a minute, depending on your system. But, if you have patience, this\n211: is all you need to know. Always run this command before pushing your changes to\n212: GitHub.\n213: \n214: If you take a look at the tox config in `pyproject.toml`, you'll see that tox\n215: runs tests in multiple environments, including `ruff-check` and `ruff-format`\n216: environments that lint the source code for issues and a `docs` environment\n217: that tests that the documentation can be built. You can also limit tox to just\n218: test specific environments using the `-e` option, e.g. to run just unit tests\n219: on Python 3.13:\n220: \n221: ```console\n222: $ tox -e 3.13\n223: ```\n224: \n225: To learn more, see the [tox documentation](https://tox.readthedocs.io/) .\n226: \n227: Before submitting a pull request, we recommend running:\n228: \n229: ```console\n230: $ tox\n231: ```\n232: \n233: This will locally run similar tests to what we use in our CI runs and help us to\n234: merge high-quality contributions.\n235: \n236: ### Running unit tests\n237: \n238: Under the hood, `tox -e 3.13` will use [pytest](https://docs.pytest.org/)\n239: as the test runner. We can also use it directly to run all tests:\n240: \n241: ```console\n242: $ pytest\n243: ```\n244: \n245: pytest has lots of possibilities, so you'll have to dive into their docs and\n246: plugins to get full benefit from it. To get you interested, here are some\n247: examples.\n248: \n249: We can limit to just tests in a single directory to save time:\n250: \n251: ```console\n252: $ pytest tests/http/\n253: ```\n254: \n255: With the help of the `pytest-xdist` plugin, we can run tests with four Python\n256: processes in parallel, which usually cuts the test time in half or more:\n257: \n258: ```console\n259: $ pytest -n 4\n260: ```\n261: \n262: Another useful feature from `pytest-xdist`, is the possibility to stop on the\n263: first test failure, watch the file system for changes, and then rerun the\n264: tests. This makes for a very quick code-test cycle:\n265: \n266: ```console\n267: $ pytest -f    # or --looponfail\n268: ```\n269: \n270: With the help of the pytest-cov plugin, we can get a report on what parts of\n271: the given module are covered by the test suite:\n272: \n273: ```console\n274: $ pytest --cov\n275: ```\n276: \n277: /// tip\n278: Up to date test coverage statistics can also be viewed online at\n279: [Codecov](https://codecov.io/gh/mopidy/mopidy).\n280: ///\n281: \n282: If we want to speed up the test suite, we can even get a list of the ten\n283: slowest tests:\n284: \n285: ```console\n286: $ pytest --durations=10\n287: ```\n288: \n289: By now, you should be convinced that running pytest directly during\n290: development can be very useful.\n291: \n292: ### Continuous integration\n293: \n294: Mopidy uses [GitHub Actions](https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy/actions) for\n295: automatically running the test suite when code is pushed to GitHub. This\n296: works both for the main Mopidy repo, but also for any forks. This way, any\n297: contributions to Mopidy through GitHub will automatically be tested, and the\n298: build status will be visible in the GitHub pull request interface, making it\n299: easier to evaluate the quality of pull requests.\n300: \n301: For each successful build, the CI setup submits code coverage data to\n302: [Codecov](https://codecov.io/gh/mopidy/mopidy). If you're out of work,\n303: Codecov might help you find areas in the code which could need better test\n304: coverage.\n305: \n306: ### Style checking and linting\n307: \n308: We're quite pedantic about codestyle and try hard to keep the Mopidy\n309: code base a very clean and nice place to work in.\n310: \n311: Luckily, you can get very far by using the [ruff](https://github.com/astral-sh/ruff) linter to check your code for issues before\n312: submitting a pull request. Mopidy's ruff rules are configured in `pyproject.toml`.\n313: You can either run the `ruff-check` tox environment, like our CI setup will do\n314: on your pull request:\n315: \n316: ```console\n317: $ tox -e ruff-check\n318: ```\n319: \n320: Or you can run ruff directly:\n321: \n322: ```console\n323: $ ruff .\n324: ```\n325: \n326: If successful, the command will not print anything at all.\n327: \n328: /// tip\n329: In some rare cases it doesn't make sense to listen to ruff's warnings. In\n330: those cases, ignore the check by appending `# noqa: <warning code>` to\n331: the source line that triggers the warning. The `# noqa` part will make\n332: ruff skip all checks on the line, while the warning code will help other\n333: developers lookup what you are ignoring.\n334: ///\n335: \n336: ## Writing documentation\n337: \n338: Documentation lives in the `docs/` directory and is written in Markdown.\n339: We use [Zensical](https://zensical.org/) to build the documentation site.\n340: \n341: To serve the documentation locally with live reloading, run:\n342: \n343: ```console\n344: $ zensical serve\n345: ```\n346: \n347: To build the documentation without serving it:\n348: \n349: ```console\n350: $ zensical build\n351: ```\n352: \n353: The documentation at <https://docs.mopidy.com/> is automatically updated\n354: when a change is pushed to the `mopidy/mopidy` repo at GitHub.\n355: \n356: ## Working on extensions\n357: \n358: Much of the above also applies to Mopidy extensions, though they're often a bit\n359: simpler. They don't have documentation sites and their test suites are either\n360: small and fast, or sadly missing entirely. Most of them use tox to run various\n361: linters, and pytest can be used to run their test suites.\n362: \n363: ### Installing extensions\n364: \n365: As always, the `mopidy` virtualenv should be active when working on\n366: extensions:\n367: \n368: ```console\n369: $ . ~/mopidy-dev/.venv/bin/activate\n370: ```\n371: \n372: Just like with non-development Mopidy installations, you can install extensions\n373: using pip:\n374: \n375: ```console\n376: $ pip install mopidy-scrobbler\n377: ```\n378: \n379: Installing an extension from its Git repo works the same way as with Mopidy\n380: itself. First, go to the Mopidy workspace:\n381: \n382: ```console\n383: $ cd ~/mopidy-dev/\n384: ```\n385: \n386: Clone the desired Mopidy extension:\n387: \n388: ```console\n389: $ git clone https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy-spotify.git\n390: ```\n391: \n392: Change to the newly created extension directory:\n393: \n394: ```console\n395: $ cd ~/mopidy-dev/mopidy-spotify/\n396: ```\n397: \n398: Then, install the extension in \"editable\" mode, so that it can be imported from\n399: anywhere inside the virtualenv and the extension is registered and discoverable\n400: through `importlib`:\n401: \n402: ```console\n403: $ pip install --editable .\n404: ```\n405: \n406: Every extension will have a `README.rst` file. It may contain information\n407: about extra dependencies required, development process, etc. Extensions usually\n408: have a changelog in their GitHub releases page.\n409: \n410: ### Upgrading extensions\n411: \n412: Extensions often have a much quicker life cycle than Mopidy itself, often with\n413: daily releases in periods of active development. To find outdated extensions in\n414: your virtualenv, you can run:\n415: \n416: ```console\n417: $ pip list --outdated\n418: ```\n419: \n420: To upgrade an extension installed with pip, simply use pip:\n421: \n422: ```console\n423: $ pip install --upgrade mopidy-scrobbler\n424: ```\n425: \n426: To upgrade an extension installed from a Git repo, it's usually enough to pull\n427: the new changes in:\n428: \n429: ```console\n430: $ cd ~/mopidy-dev/mopidy-spotify/\n431: $ git pull\n432: ```\n433: \n434: Of course, if you have local modifications, you'll need to stash these away on\n435: a branch or similar first.\n436: \n437: Depending on the changes to the extension, it may be necessary to update the\n438: metadata about the extension package by installing it in \"editable\" mode\n439: again:\n440: \n441: ```console\n442: $ pip install --editable .\n443: ```\n444: \n445: ## Contribution workflow\n446: \n447: Before you being, make sure you've read the contributing page and the\n448: guidelines there. This section will focus more on the practical workflow.\n449: \n450: For the examples, we're making a change to Mopidy. Approximately the same\n451: workflow should work for most Mopidy extensions too.\n452: \n453: ### Setting up Git remotes\n454: \n455: Assuming we already have a local Git clone of the upstream Git repo in\n456: `/mopidy-dev/mopidy/`, we can run `git remote -v` to list the\n457: configured remotes of the repo:\n458: \n459: ```console\n460: $ git remote -v\n461: origin  https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git (fetch)\n462: origin  https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git (push)\n463: ```\n464: \n465: For clarity, we can rename the `origin` remote to `upstream`:\n466: \n467: ```console\n468: $ git remote rename origin upstream\n469: $ git remote -v\n470: upstream        https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git (fetch)\n471: upstream        https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git (push)\n472: ```\n473: \n474: If you haven't already, [fork the repository](https://help.github.com/en/articles/fork-a-repo) to your own GitHub account.\n475: \n476: Then, add the new fork as a remote to your local clone:\n477: \n478: ```console\n479: $ git remote add myuser git@github.com:myuser/mopidy.git\n480: ```\n481: \n482: The end result is that you have both the upstream repo and your own fork as\n483: remotes:\n484: \n485: ```console\n486: $ git remote -v\n487: myuser  git@github.com:myuser/mopidy.git (fetch)\n488: myuser  git@github.com:myuser/mopidy.git (push)\n489: upstream        https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git (fetch)\n490: upstream        https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git (push)\n491: ```\n492: \n493: ### Creating a branch\n494: \n495: Fetch the latest data from all remotes without affecting your working\n496: directory:\n497: \n498: ```console\n499: $ git remote update --prune\n500: ```\n501: \n502: Now, we are ready to create and checkout a new branch off of the upstream\n503: `main` branch for our work:\n504: \n505: ```console\n506: $ git checkout -b fix-crash-on-foo upstream/main\n507: ```\n508: \n509: Do the work, while remembering to adhere to code style, test the changes, make\n510: necessary updates to the documentation, and making small commits with good\n511: commit messages. All as described in contributing and elsewhere in\n512: the devenv guide.\n513: \n514: ### Creating a pull request\n515: \n516: When everything is done and committed, push the branch to your fork on GitHub:\n517: \n518: ```console\n519: $ git push myuser fix-crash-on-foo\n520: ```\n521: \n522: Go to the repository on GitHub where you want the change merged, in this case\n523: <https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy>, and [create a pull request](https://help.github.com/en/articles/creating-a-pull-request).\n524: \n525: ### Updating a pull request\n526: \n527: When the pull request is created, our CI setup will run all tests on it.\n528: If something fails, you'll usually get a notification from GitHub.\n529: You might as well just fix the issues right away,\n530: as we won't merge a pull request without all CI builds being green.\n531: See running-tests on how to run the same tests locally as\n532: our CI setup runs on your pull request.\n533: \n534: When you've fixed the issues, you can update the pull request simply by pushing\n535: more commits to the same branch in your fork:\n536: \n537: ```console\n538: $ git push myuser fix-crash-on-foo\n539: ```\n540: \n541: Likewise, when you get review comments from other developers on your pull\n542: request, you're expected to create additional commits which addresses the\n543: comments. Push them to your branch so that the pull request is updated.\n\n(End of file - total 543 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\n# Development environment\n\nThis page describes a common development setup for working with Mopidy and\nMopidy extensions. Of course, there may be other ways that work better for you\nand the tools you use, but here's one recommended way to do it.\n\n## Initial setup\n\nThe following steps help you get a good initial setup. They build on each other\nto some degree, so if you're not very familiar with Python development it might\nbe wise to proceed in the order laid out here.\n\n### Install Mopidy the regular way\n\nInstall Mopidy the regular way. Mopidy has some non-Python dependencies which\nmay be tricky to install. Thus we recommend to always start with a full regular\nMopidy install, as described in installation. That is, if you're running\ne.g. Debian, start with installing Mopidy from Debian packages.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"docs/about/devenv.md","time":{"start":1776094038521,"end":1776094038529}}}]}
